1
00:00:54,413 --> 00:00:57,012
This is a true story about friendship
that runs deeper than blood.

2
00:00:58,931 --> 00:01:02,289
This is my story & that of the only 3
friends in my life who truly mattered.

3
00:01:04,168 --> 00:01:07,407
Two of them were killers who
never made it past the age of thirty.

4
00:01:08,246 --> 00:01:11,445
The other is a non-practicing attorney
living with the pain of his past...

5
00:01:11,925 --> 00:01:14,963
...too afraid to let it go,
never confronting its horror.

6
00:01:16,882 --> 00:01:20,520
I'm the only one who could speak for
them...and the children we were.

7
00:02:57,951 --> 00:02:59,671
My three friends and
I were inseparable...

8
00:03:00,190 --> 00:03:02,509
...happy and content to live in the
closed world of Hell's Kitchen.

9
00:03:03,069 --> 00:03:05,588
The West Side streets of Manhattan
were our private playground...

10
00:03:06,027 --> 00:03:10,105
...a cement kingdom where we felt we
were nothing less than absolute rulers.

11
00:03:12,744 --> 00:03:14,743
Hell's Kitchen was populated
by an uneasy blend of...

12
00:03:14,823 --> 00:03:16,702
Irish, Italian, Puerto Rican,

13
00:03:16,742 --> 00:03:20,180
and Eastern European laborers.
Hard men living hard lives.

14
00:03:30,335 --> 00:03:32,854
We lived in railroad apartments
inside red brick tenements.

15
00:03:33,534 --> 00:03:35,773
Few mothers worked and all had
trouble with the men they married.

16
00:03:43,129 --> 00:03:45,368
I buried one fucking wife,
I could bury another one!

17
00:03:51,645 --> 00:03:54,083
Domestic violence was a cottage
industry in Hell's Kitchen.

18
00:03:54,563 --> 00:03:56,682
Yet, there was no divorce
and few separations.

19
00:03:56,762 --> 00:03:58,681
The will of the Church was forceful.

20
00:03:59,361 --> 00:04:01,680
For a marriage to end,
someone usually had to die.

21
00:04:05,118 --> 00:04:06,637
Yet, despite the harshness of life...

22
00:04:07,237 --> 00:04:09,756
...Hell's Kitchen offered the kids
on its streets a safety net...

23
00:04:09,955 --> 00:04:11,395
...enjoyed by few other neighborhoods.

24
00:04:12,914 --> 00:04:15,473
Crimes against people of the
neighborhood were not permitted.

25
00:04:16,192 --> 00:04:18,431
When they did occur, the punishment
doled out was severe...

26
00:04:18,991 --> 00:04:20,270
...and, in some cases, final.

27
00:04:21,230 --> 00:04:24,108
A drug dealer from uptown
moved heroin into Hell's Kitchen.

28
00:04:24,828 --> 00:04:27,427
A packet killed the twelve-year old
son of a Puerto Rican numbers runner.

29
00:04:28,186 --> 00:04:30,105
It was the last packet
the dealer ever sold.

30
00:04:31,864 --> 00:04:34,783
Hell's Kitchen was a place of
innocence...ruled by corruption.

31
00:04:37,622 --> 00:04:40,220
My friends and I spent lots of time
inside Holy Angels.

32
00:04:40,260 --> 00:04:42,019
We each served as altar boys.

33
00:04:42,659 --> 00:04:44,378
Everyone wanted to work
funeral masses,

34
00:04:44,418 --> 00:04:46,257
since the funeral included a $3 fee...

35
00:04:46,657 --> 00:04:48,536
...and more if you looked
sufficiently somber.

36
00:04:50,495 --> 00:04:52,614
There was an active competition
between the four of us...

37
00:04:52,694 --> 00:04:54,293
...to come up with the best
and boldest prank.

38
00:04:55,693 --> 00:04:57,572
Two weeks into the new school year,

39
00:04:57,612 --> 00:04:59,531
I found the nun's clacker in
the school hallway...

40
00:04:59,811 --> 00:05:01,290
...and I was ready for the big leagues.

41
00:05:03,249 --> 00:05:05,168
In church, it was used to alert
the girls as to when...

42
00:05:05,328 --> 00:05:07,407
...they should stand, sit,
kneel and genuflect...

43
00:05:07,567 --> 00:05:09,726
...all based on the number of
times the clacker was pressed.

44
00:05:10,285 --> 00:05:12,844
In my pocket, it was cause for havoc.

45
00:05:21,999 --> 00:05:26,197
You will be defenders of the faith.
You will be soldiers of Christ.

46
00:05:27,157 --> 00:05:28,516
And you will receive the gifts...

47
00:05:29,036 --> 00:05:29,955
...of the Holy Spirit.

48
00:05:37,392 --> 00:05:38,791
It's gonna be a great day and your...

49
00:05:38,951 --> 00:05:42,149
...parents will be proud of you.
When you were baptized...

50
00:05:42,629 --> 00:05:44,868
...godparents made promises for you.
And now...

51
00:05:44,908 --> 00:05:46,747
-You're gonna confirm those promises.
-Let me have the clacker.

52
00:05:47,627 --> 00:05:48,826
What clacker?

53
00:05:48,986 --> 00:05:49,626
Now!

54
00:05:50,585 --> 00:05:52,064
Let everyone rise.

55
00:05:55,503 --> 00:05:56,342
Let us pray.

56
00:06:05,738 --> 00:06:07,497
Nuns are such easy targets.

57
00:06:09,456 --> 00:06:11,695
John and I spent more time in
church than the others.

58
00:06:12,014 --> 00:06:14,653
We were the only two in the group to give
any thought of entering the priesthood.

59
00:06:15,093 --> 00:06:17,452
And John and I were intrigued by
the powers the priest was given.

60
00:06:17,612 --> 00:06:19,890
A secret world of betrayal
and deceit, where people...

61
00:06:20,050 --> 00:06:22,529
...openly admitted dark misdeeds
and vile indiscretions.

62
00:06:22,929 --> 00:06:25,088
Confession was better than any
book we could get our hands on,

63
00:06:25,248 --> 00:06:27,367
or any movie we could see,
because the sins were real...

64
00:06:28,046 --> 00:06:29,126
...committed by people we knew.

65
00:06:29,885 --> 00:06:32,564
The temptation to be part of that
was far too great to resist.

66
00:06:32,724 --> 00:06:33,724
If we get caught, they'll burn us.

67
00:06:34,923 --> 00:06:36,202
What if our mothers are out there?

68
00:06:36,842 --> 00:06:38,721
What if we end up hearing
their confessions?

69
00:06:39,161 --> 00:06:40,360
What if we hear something worse?

70
00:06:41,000 --> 00:06:41,800
Like what?

71
00:06:41,999 --> 00:06:45,038
Like a murder. What if
somebody cops to a murder?

72
00:06:45,837 --> 00:06:49,356
Relax. All we've got to do is sit back,
listen and remember not to laugh.

73
00:06:57,072 --> 00:06:59,631
Seconds later,
our booth comes to life.

74
00:07:00,110 --> 00:07:02,149
I...sleep with married men.

75
00:07:03,709 --> 00:07:04,908
Men with families.

76
00:07:06,267 --> 00:07:09,945
In the morning, I tell myself
it's the last time, but it never is.

77
00:07:12,584 --> 00:07:13,664
Yes?

78
00:07:14,783 --> 00:07:17,981
You see, I'm...I'm pregnant.

79
00:07:21,420 --> 00:07:23,099
The father?

80
00:07:23,379 --> 00:07:24,378
Take a number.

81
00:07:25,218 --> 00:07:26,137
What are you going to do?

82
00:07:27,097 --> 00:07:28,576
I know what you want me to do.

83
00:07:29,456 --> 00:07:30,815
And I know what I should do.

84
00:07:32,374 --> 00:07:34,013
I just don't know what I'm gonna do.

85
00:07:36,892 --> 00:07:38,051
Look, I gotta go.

86
00:07:38,931 --> 00:07:41,650
Thanks for listening, fellas.
I really appreciate it.

87
00:07:42,289 --> 00:07:43,768
I know you'll keep it to yourselves.

88
00:07:50,365 --> 00:07:51,165
She knew.

89
00:07:51,804 --> 00:07:53,004
Yeah, she knew.

90
00:07:53,364 --> 00:07:54,963
Why do you think she told us all that?

91
00:07:55,922 --> 00:07:58,481
I don't know. I guess
she had to tell somebody.

92
00:08:02,759 --> 00:08:05,078
Father Robert Carrillo was
a longshoreman's son...

93
00:08:05,238 --> 00:08:07,796
...who was as comfortable sitting on
a bar stool in a back alley saloon...

94
00:08:07,956 --> 00:08:09,995
...as he was standing at the altar
during High Mass.

95
00:08:10,675 --> 00:08:13,554
He had toyed with a life of petty
crime before finding his calling.

96
00:08:13,754 --> 00:08:16,272
He was a friend...a friend who
just happened to be a priest.

97
00:08:16,512 --> 00:08:17,791
You know what crap like
that does to your body?

98
00:08:18,271 --> 00:08:21,230
Come on, Father, it beats smoking.
And it's cheaper, too.

99
00:08:21,949 --> 00:08:25,028
Maybe.
So, what do you hear, anything?

100
00:08:25,668 --> 00:08:26,827
No, nothing.

101
00:08:26,987 --> 00:08:28,706
I hear you're interested
in becoming a priest.

102
00:08:29,066 --> 00:08:29,706
Who says?

103
00:08:30,825 --> 00:08:33,424
Word is you want to get the
feel of a confessional booth.

104
00:08:34,223 --> 00:08:35,703
I don't know what you're
talking about, Father.

105
00:08:36,062 --> 00:08:36,702
You don't?

106
00:08:37,781 --> 00:08:39,301
Maybe I got the wrong information.

107
00:08:39,820 --> 00:08:40,820
I guess you did.

108
00:08:42,539 --> 00:08:43,818
I'll see you later tonight.

109
00:08:44,378 --> 00:08:45,418
What's tonight?

110
00:08:46,297 --> 00:08:48,216
I gotta drop some books
and magazines off...

111
00:08:48,296 --> 00:08:50,135
...for the elderly and disabled
around the neighborhood.

112
00:08:50,295 --> 00:08:51,415
Your mother said you'd love to help.

113
00:08:51,894 --> 00:08:53,014
I bet she did.

114
00:08:55,413 --> 00:08:58,931
Shakes...l don't want you
getting into any trouble.

115
00:08:59,451 --> 00:09:01,010
Come on, Father, you know I never do.

116
00:09:01,210 --> 00:09:03,129
That's all I wish for
you and your friends.

117
00:09:03,689 --> 00:09:04,288
That's it?

118
00:09:04,368 --> 00:09:06,047
That's it. Nothing else,
I swear, that's it.

119
00:09:06,447 --> 00:09:07,726
You know, a priest shouldn't swear.

120
00:09:08,406 --> 00:09:10,565
And kids shouldn't be listening
to other people's confessions.

121
00:09:10,645 --> 00:09:11,565
I'll see you tonight.

122
00:09:11,884 --> 00:09:12,684
All right...see you.

123
00:09:17,162 --> 00:09:19,321
Michael was the most sexually
experienced of our group,

124
00:09:19,481 --> 00:09:21,879
which meant that he kissed a girl
on more than one occasion.

125
00:09:22,399 --> 00:09:26,197
But his real love was Carol Martinez,
Hell's Kitchen's half-breed.

126
00:09:26,277 --> 00:09:29,156
Half Puerto Rican, half Irish,
she was raised by her father,

127
00:09:29,316 --> 00:09:30,635
her mother having died at childbirth.

128
00:09:31,075 --> 00:09:34,353
Carol stayed pretty much to herself but
was always comfortable in our company.

129
00:09:35,193 --> 00:09:36,192
We could always count on Carol...

130
00:09:36,272 --> 00:09:38,391
...to stand sentry on the first night
of the Ice Capades.

131
00:09:39,151 --> 00:09:41,030
While crowds of families lined
the front of the Garden...

132
00:09:41,110 --> 00:09:42,189
...waiting to see the skaters perform...

133
00:09:42,909 --> 00:09:44,508
...we each had one eye in a hole...

134
00:09:44,588 --> 00:09:47,027
...watching two dozen beautiful
and nearly naked women...

135
00:09:47,067 --> 00:09:48,466
...get into their skaters' outfits.

136
00:09:51,585 --> 00:09:53,064
This is what heaven must be about.

137
00:10:01,739 --> 00:10:03,139
Carol, you want to take a look?

138
00:10:03,938 --> 00:10:05,498
Like it's something I haven't seen?

139
00:10:06,137 --> 00:10:08,056
You're so lucky!

140
00:10:09,096 --> 00:10:13,374
She's so beautiful. My God, I could
die now and I wouldn't be sad.

141
00:10:13,733 --> 00:10:15,133
When my friends and I were young,

142
00:10:15,213 --> 00:10:17,132
...Hell's Kitchen was run
by a man named King Benny.

143
00:10:18,531 --> 00:10:21,370
When he was young, King Benny
was a hit man for Lucky Luciano.

144
00:10:21,690 --> 00:10:24,568
Lucky Luciano did a lot of good for
this country during World War ll.

145
00:10:24,728 --> 00:10:26,967
But you ain't gonna read about
that in any fucking history book!

146
00:10:27,567 --> 00:10:30,525
There was talk King Benny was
the shooter of "Mad Dog Coll"...

147
00:10:30,725 --> 00:10:34,483
...that prick on West 23rd Street.
He ran bootleg with "Dutch" Schultz.

148
00:10:34,963 --> 00:10:37,682
And he opened up a couple of clubs
with "Tough Tony" Anastasia.

149
00:10:37,921 --> 00:10:41,120
I was 14 when I first heard
about him. The story goes:

150
00:10:41,360 --> 00:10:43,159
As a kid, he wasn't much of anything.

151
00:10:44,278 --> 00:10:46,477
He was always getting the shit
kicked out of him in street fights.

152
00:10:46,837 --> 00:10:50,035
And then one day, and who the
fuck knows why, some Irish guy...

153
00:10:50,395 --> 00:10:53,913
...about 25 years old,
he takes King Benny...

154
00:10:54,073 --> 00:10:55,712
...and he flings him down
a flight of stairs.

155
00:10:56,032 --> 00:10:58,551
King Benny breaks all
his teeth in the front.

156
00:10:59,031 --> 00:11:00,150
You know what King Benny does?

157
00:11:01,190 --> 00:11:04,748
He waits. He waits 8 years...

158
00:11:04,908 --> 00:11:06,227
...to get even with that prick.

159
00:11:06,787 --> 00:11:08,586
He walks into a public bath house.

160
00:11:08,746 --> 00:11:09,825
The guy's soaking in the tub.

161
00:11:10,945 --> 00:11:14,823
King Benny takes out his front teeth.
He lays them down on the sink.

162
00:11:16,902 --> 00:11:18,621
Then he looks over at
the guy and says,

163
00:11:20,380 --> 00:11:23,459
"When I look in the mirror,
I see your face."

164
00:11:24,298 --> 00:11:25,578
Then he pulls out a gun...

165
00:11:26,977 --> 00:11:28,736
...and he shoots the guy twice
in each leg.

166
00:11:32,294 --> 00:11:33,254
Then he says to the guy:

167
00:11:33,893 --> 00:11:37,252
"Now, when you take
a bath, you see mine."

168
00:11:38,931 --> 00:11:40,930
No one ever fucked with
King Benny after that.

169
00:11:42,409 --> 00:11:43,169
Revenge!

170
00:11:45,008 --> 00:11:45,927
Revenge!

171
00:11:49,885 --> 00:11:50,845
Can I talk to you for a minute?

172
00:11:51,565 --> 00:11:54,243
I'd like to work for you.
Help you out, whatever you need.

173
00:11:54,883 --> 00:11:57,122
You're the butcher's kid...am I right?

174
00:11:59,601 --> 00:12:01,120
What kind of a job are you looking for?

175
00:12:01,480 --> 00:12:02,759
Whatever, it doesn't matter.

176
00:12:03,039 --> 00:12:04,718
It doesn't matter?

177
00:12:06,837 --> 00:12:08,876
Everybody says this is the
place to come for jobs.

178
00:12:09,396 --> 00:12:10,515
Who is everybody?

179
00:12:10,875 --> 00:12:12,314
People from the neighborhood.

180
00:12:13,034 --> 00:12:16,232
Let me ask you, what
the fuck do they know?

181
00:12:17,032 --> 00:12:18,311
They know you got jobs.

182
00:12:23,828 --> 00:12:25,428
Sorry I wasted your time.

183
00:12:26,867 --> 00:12:27,906
Hold on a sec!

184
00:12:29,865 --> 00:12:31,465
Come back tomorrow if you want to work.

185
00:12:31,784 --> 00:12:33,384
-What time tomorrow?
-Any time.

186
00:12:33,584 --> 00:12:34,543
You'll be here?

187
00:12:35,143 --> 00:12:36,422
I'm always here.

188
00:12:43,658 --> 00:12:46,177
My first job for King Benny
paid $25 a week and...

189
00:12:46,337 --> 00:12:48,096
...ate up only 40 minutes of my time.

190
00:12:48,976 --> 00:12:51,734
In the dark club room, one of the guys
would hand me a crumpled paper bag...

191
00:12:51,894 --> 00:12:54,253
...and direct me to one of the two
local police precincts for delivery.

192
00:12:55,173 --> 00:12:56,692
It was a perfect way
to handle payouts.

193
00:12:57,212 --> 00:13:00,090
Come on, let's go! Right here.

194
00:13:00,250 --> 00:13:01,729
Let's see what kind of cash
you've got in that bag.

195
00:13:01,929 --> 00:13:03,968
You gotta be nuts! Do you
know who you're taking off?

196
00:13:04,328 --> 00:13:06,167
Yeah, we know, and
we're scared shitless.

197
00:13:07,487 --> 00:13:10,045
Give me the bag.
Give me the fucking bag!

198
00:13:10,205 --> 00:13:14,323
Hey, what you do there? Answer me!
What you do there?

199
00:13:14,843 --> 00:13:16,122
This time they took my money!

200
00:13:16,282 --> 00:13:17,721
You took the money from the boy?

201
00:13:17,881 --> 00:13:18,921
The money they took is in the bag.

202
00:13:19,121 --> 00:13:19,720
Let me have the bag.

203
00:13:19,920 --> 00:13:20,520
Fuck you!

204
00:13:21,999 --> 00:13:22,719
How about now?

205
00:13:22,959 --> 00:13:23,918
All right, take it easy.

206
00:13:23,998 --> 00:13:27,756
You're not smart anymore.
This make you stupid.

207
00:13:27,916 --> 00:13:28,836
Let me have the bag.

208
00:13:32,474 --> 00:13:33,354
Now, go!

209
00:13:33,594 --> 00:13:34,353
What about them?

210
00:13:34,513 --> 00:13:35,153
You care?

211
00:13:35,353 --> 00:13:37,911
Then go! Go! Run!

212
00:13:39,111 --> 00:13:41,590
I need somebody with me.
What if the old guy hadn't showed?

213
00:13:42,229 --> 00:13:43,189
What you need?

214
00:13:43,349 --> 00:13:44,628
My friends.

215
00:13:44,788 --> 00:13:47,586
Your friends? What do
you think, this is camp?

216
00:13:47,746 --> 00:13:50,305
These kids, you can trust.
I've known them half my life!

217
00:13:51,984 --> 00:13:54,023
Okay, get your friends.

218
00:13:54,623 --> 00:13:57,661
Father Bobby knew we worked for
King Benny, and he wasn't pleased.

219
00:13:58,101 --> 00:14:00,620
He wasn't worried about the
pocket money, but the next step...

220
00:14:01,020 --> 00:14:02,299
...when they ask you to pick up a gun.

221
00:14:02,779 --> 00:14:04,258
He didn't want that to happen to us.

222
00:14:04,818 --> 00:14:06,617
You think running for King
Benny is a good idea?

223
00:14:06,777 --> 00:14:07,417
It pays.

224
00:14:07,696 --> 00:14:08,736
A lot of things pay.

225
00:14:08,816 --> 00:14:09,695
Not like this.

226
00:14:12,054 --> 00:14:14,133
Most priests liked to
preach from the pulpit.

227
00:14:14,573 --> 00:14:17,611
Father Bobby liked to talk during the
bump and shove of a pick-up game.

228
00:14:18,411 --> 00:14:19,171
Good shot!

229
00:14:21,330 --> 00:14:22,729
I found an art class for you to take.

230
00:14:22,889 --> 00:14:24,328
You know I can't afford
to take any art classes.

231
00:14:24,488 --> 00:14:26,647
You don't have to pay anything.
The teacher's a friend of mine.

232
00:14:27,287 --> 00:14:29,765
It could be nothing but
a waste of time, Father.

233
00:14:29,925 --> 00:14:31,604
Maybe, or it could be the first step.

234
00:14:31,844 --> 00:14:32,844
First step to what?

235
00:14:33,044 --> 00:14:34,003
Doing something with your life.

236
00:14:34,163 --> 00:14:35,602
You never know, it may
help you get out of here.

237
00:14:35,722 --> 00:14:36,482
You all can get out of here.

238
00:14:36,642 --> 00:14:38,321
Guys, are we gonna talk
or play basketball?

239
00:14:40,800 --> 00:14:42,319
Listen, I got a story
I want to tell you.

240
00:14:42,519 --> 00:14:45,038
It ain't the one about the lepers, is it?
Cause that one gave me nightmares.

241
00:14:45,238 --> 00:14:48,156
No lepers. Michelangelo.
He was born poor, just like you guys.

242
00:14:48,316 --> 00:14:49,715
He was a painter, he was a sculptor.

243
00:14:50,035 --> 00:14:53,234
He takes this job from the Pope.
Good money, good work.

244
00:14:54,393 --> 00:14:56,472
Okay, Father, but why'd
the Pope call him?

245
00:14:56,632 --> 00:14:58,711
Because the Pope was looking for
the best guy he could find...

246
00:14:58,871 --> 00:15:00,270
...to paint the ceiling
of his church in Rome.

247
00:15:00,470 --> 00:15:02,069
It don't sound like
that big a job, Father.

248
00:15:02,349 --> 00:15:03,628
Well, for Michelangelo it was.

249
00:15:04,068 --> 00:15:05,787
Michelangelo needed the job...

250
00:15:05,947 --> 00:15:07,826
...because it paid more money
than he ever had in his life.

251
00:15:08,506 --> 00:15:11,145
And that way, he could pay off the loan
sharks that were chasing his father down.

252
00:15:11,265 --> 00:15:11,904
What's his father?

253
00:15:12,664 --> 00:15:15,582
He was like a low-level...con guy.

254
00:15:15,742 --> 00:15:17,222
Conned people out of money,
goats, sheep...

255
00:15:17,302 --> 00:15:18,021
Goats?

256
00:15:18,181 --> 00:15:19,461
Chickens, whatever he could, you know.

257
00:15:19,620 --> 00:15:20,260
-Chickens?
-Chickens?

258
00:15:20,860 --> 00:15:21,579
You know what happened?

259
00:15:23,059 --> 00:15:24,738
He painted a ceiling no
one will ever forget.

260
00:15:24,978 --> 00:15:26,697
Painted it like he was touched
by the hand of God.

261
00:15:27,536 --> 00:15:28,696
Did he pay off the loans?

262
00:15:28,856 --> 00:15:29,935
Every single one of them.

263
00:15:31,055 --> 00:15:32,894
How long did it take him,
painting the ceiling and all?

264
00:15:33,054 --> 00:15:34,493
It took him about 9 years.

265
00:15:34,853 --> 00:15:35,852
9 years?!

266
00:15:36,132 --> 00:15:37,132
That's a big ceiling!

267
00:15:37,571 --> 00:15:40,130
I had a Puerto Rican do my
whole apartment in two days.

268
00:15:40,330 --> 00:15:41,210
And he had a bum leg.

269
00:15:41,569 --> 00:15:43,489
You know, I don't know what
I'm gonna do with you guys.

270
00:15:44,968 --> 00:15:47,207
Hey, just give us a job painting,
and leave the rest to us.

271
00:15:47,367 --> 00:15:48,446
You know what it was?
The Sistine Chapel!

272
00:15:48,766 --> 00:15:50,405
Sixteenth Chapel?

273
00:15:50,565 --> 00:15:51,325
Who painted the other fifteen?

274
00:15:59,600 --> 00:16:03,758
Outside events meant little. In a society
changing radically by the hour...

275
00:16:03,918 --> 00:16:06,557
...we watched the images scatter
nightly across the T.V. screens.

276
00:16:06,997 --> 00:16:09,995
Young protesters spoke about how they
were going to change our lives...

277
00:16:10,075 --> 00:16:13,593
...and fix the world. But while
they shouted their slogans...

278
00:16:14,633 --> 00:16:16,032
...my friends and I went to
funeral services...

279
00:16:16,112 --> 00:16:17,591
...for the young men
of Hell's Kitchen...

280
00:16:17,911 --> 00:16:19,950
...who came back from Vietnam
in body bags.

281
00:16:21,230 --> 00:16:23,588
We viewed with skepticism
the faces on television...

282
00:16:24,668 --> 00:16:26,987
...those protected by money and
upper-middle-class standing.

283
00:16:30,225 --> 00:16:33,024
A growing army of feminists
marched across the country...

284
00:16:33,703 --> 00:16:36,782
...demanding equality.
Yet, our mothers still cooked...

285
00:16:36,942 --> 00:16:39,500
...and cared for men who abused
them mentally and physically.

286
00:16:41,539 --> 00:16:44,258
For me and my friends, these
developments carried no weight.

287
00:16:45,138 --> 00:16:48,456
They might as well have occurred in
another country...in another century.

288
00:16:49,695 --> 00:16:51,095
Our attention was elsewhere.

289
00:16:51,854 --> 00:16:54,973
We sat with Father Bobby in a third
floor hospital ward, visiting John...

290
00:16:55,133 --> 00:16:56,572
...hoping he'd recover from
a punctured lung.

291
00:16:56,972 --> 00:16:59,451
A gift from one of his mother's
over-zealous boyfriends.

292
00:16:59,610 --> 00:17:02,809
I hope you like these.
You better not tell me you don't.

293
00:17:07,207 --> 00:17:09,406
Father Bobby didn't let
that situation rest.

294
00:17:09,605 --> 00:17:11,045
I gave on Sunday.
I'm in a rush, okay?

295
00:17:11,125 --> 00:17:11,724
John Reilly.

296
00:17:11,804 --> 00:17:13,084
The little punk!

297
00:17:13,603 --> 00:17:15,642
He got out of line, so I put him
back in line. No big deal.

298
00:17:15,802 --> 00:17:17,082
You put him in the hospital.

299
00:17:17,242 --> 00:17:20,600
He's alive, ain't he? Look, if he's
smart, he learned himself a lesson.

300
00:17:21,200 --> 00:17:23,119
What are you? About 220, 230?

301
00:17:24,318 --> 00:17:27,277
You're a big guy. How much
you think John Reilly weighs?

302
00:17:28,076 --> 00:17:31,035
80, 85?
That's not even a featherweight.

303
00:17:32,114 --> 00:17:34,073
If this were a fight, you'd
be way out of your division.

304
00:17:34,353 --> 00:17:37,551
Look, it was a slap, it was nothing.

305
00:17:38,391 --> 00:17:40,030
Well, next time you'll be meeting me.

306
00:17:40,710 --> 00:17:44,348
And I may not be in your division, but
I do weigh more than 85 pounds.

307
00:17:45,507 --> 00:17:48,066
And you won't need a doctor when
I'm done, you'll need a priest...

308
00:17:48,906 --> 00:17:50,185
...to pray over your body.

309
00:17:54,263 --> 00:17:55,542
See you in church.

310
00:18:01,220 --> 00:18:03,379
Father Bobby would've
made a good hit man.

311
00:18:03,538 --> 00:18:06,097
It's a shame we lost
him to the other side.

312
00:18:08,736 --> 00:18:11,974
We were down 7-6 in the last inning
of a sewer-to-sewer stickball game...

313
00:18:12,174 --> 00:18:14,533
...against Hector Maldonado...
and three of his friends.

314
00:18:16,012 --> 00:18:18,371
Come on, Davy...take this chump out.
He got nothing!

315
00:18:18,651 --> 00:18:19,291
Shut up!

316
00:18:19,850 --> 00:18:20,610
Who's that?

317
00:18:20,890 --> 00:18:21,889
His sister.

318
00:18:23,009 --> 00:18:23,648
What happened to her?

319
00:18:24,288 --> 00:18:26,847
I'm not sure, some kind of cancer
got in her legs or something.

320
00:18:27,047 --> 00:18:28,126
Worry about the game, come on.

321
00:18:29,565 --> 00:18:31,684
Come on, Davy, strike the scumbag out.

322
00:18:31,724 --> 00:18:33,963
He can't touch you Davy,
he can't touch you.

323
00:18:34,083 --> 00:18:36,162
Hey, while you don't got any
legs, you got a lot of tongue!

324
00:18:36,522 --> 00:18:37,681
This is it...home run!

325
00:18:39,161 --> 00:18:40,240
Easy, Mike.

326
00:18:41,080 --> 00:18:42,879
What the fuck you
looking at, little dick?!

327
00:18:43,838 --> 00:18:45,118
She's nothing but charm.

328
00:18:46,197 --> 00:18:47,476
Come on, Davy!

329
00:18:47,636 --> 00:18:48,916
You can take him,
you can take him, Mikey.

330
00:18:49,116 --> 00:18:51,155
Yeah, I told you he wasn't shit, baby!

331
00:18:51,395 --> 00:18:53,154
Hey, swallow your tongue,
you little gimp bitch!

332
00:18:53,473 --> 00:18:55,073
You could've helped her
across the street...

333
00:18:55,113 --> 00:18:56,272
...or you could've bought her
an ice cream.

334
00:18:56,392 --> 00:18:57,471
You didn't have to throw the game.

335
00:18:58,071 --> 00:18:59,790
Yeah, and now we're
the Salvation Army.

336
00:19:00,110 --> 00:19:02,029
You ever wonder why there
ain't a Salvation Navy?

337
00:19:02,349 --> 00:19:04,628
Game over, losers.
Cough up the cash. A buck each.

338
00:19:06,027 --> 00:19:06,947
He's no better than you.

339
00:19:07,586 --> 00:19:08,506
He was today.

340
00:19:08,746 --> 00:19:10,105
No. You let him be.

341
00:19:10,585 --> 00:19:13,503
All because Irish, here, has a thing
for little girls with no legs.

342
00:19:13,823 --> 00:19:15,582
Look, stay away from this,
fat man, all right?

343
00:19:16,142 --> 00:19:18,981
You boys are soft like bread.
It's going to catch up to you.

344
00:19:19,341 --> 00:19:21,220
And when it does, it's
going to hurt...bad.

345
00:19:21,499 --> 00:19:24,778
What happens is our business,
not yours, okay?

346
00:19:24,818 --> 00:19:26,257
You gotta stay tough to be tough.

347
00:19:26,657 --> 00:19:28,856
Guy smells it when you're weak;
eat you like a salad.

348
00:19:29,336 --> 00:19:30,335
Do you see that street?

349
00:19:30,415 --> 00:19:33,933
That street is the dish of life,
and you boys are appetizers.

350
00:19:34,093 --> 00:19:37,292
Somebody gonna come along, eat you
up and forget about you by dessert.

351
00:19:37,571 --> 00:19:39,770
Take it easy, fat man.
It was just stickball.

352
00:19:39,930 --> 00:19:42,969
Yeah, but going soft is a habit.

353
00:19:43,129 --> 00:19:46,327
You have to keep yourself mean
and cut your life around it!

354
00:19:46,487 --> 00:19:48,446
All right, all right, calm down.

355
00:19:48,526 --> 00:19:50,525
It's like hanging out with fucking
Confucius over here.

356
00:19:50,765 --> 00:19:52,044
Be funny, limp dick.

357
00:19:52,524 --> 00:19:54,283
Look, this is just free advice
from me to you.

358
00:19:54,323 --> 00:19:56,042
You take it or you throw it away.
It don't matter.

359
00:19:56,682 --> 00:19:57,961
Thanks a lot, fat man.

360
00:19:59,920 --> 00:20:02,279
In truth, we were all surprised
by Michael's actions.

361
00:20:02,759 --> 00:20:04,278
But in his mind,
losing that game meant...

362
00:20:04,358 --> 00:20:06,677
...handing a feeling of victory
to a girl in a wheelchair...

363
00:20:07,077 --> 00:20:08,596
...was more than the right thing to do.

364
00:20:17,871 --> 00:20:19,271
Come on, let's go swimming.

365
00:20:19,670 --> 00:20:21,589
The temperature topped out
at 98 degrees...

366
00:20:21,669 --> 00:20:23,788
...on the day our lives
were forever altered.

367
00:20:24,188 --> 00:20:26,787
I'm frying like an egg up here.
I say, we get some buttered rolls,

368
00:20:26,947 --> 00:20:29,066
a couple of cold sodas, and head
down to the docks.

369
00:20:29,226 --> 00:20:31,145
Can't you feel the breeze up here?

370
00:20:31,305 --> 00:20:33,144
What breeze?
We're surrounded by a wall, genius!

371
00:20:33,304 --> 00:20:34,183
The devil couldn't stand this heat.

372
00:20:34,263 --> 00:20:35,502
Will you guys shut up, please?

373
00:20:35,622 --> 00:20:36,742
I'm trying to get my burn.

374
00:20:36,902 --> 00:20:38,181
It's 98 degrees!

375
00:20:38,621 --> 00:20:40,820
-There's some breeze up here.
-It's a hot breeze.

376
00:20:40,900 --> 00:20:43,059
We haven't hit the hot dog
vendor in a couple of weeks.

377
00:20:43,698 --> 00:20:46,297
I don't know, Mikey. That cart guy
ain't like the others.

378
00:20:46,657 --> 00:20:50,175
I mean, he gets pretty pissed, like
crazy when you try to take him off.

379
00:20:50,335 --> 00:20:53,733
We can eat hot dogs...
or we can eat air...choose.

380
00:20:55,652 --> 00:20:57,252
Air is probably safer, Mike.

381
00:20:57,491 --> 00:20:59,610
Yeah, a hot dog ain't worth
bleeding over, Mikey.

382
00:20:59,970 --> 00:21:01,729
Yeah, anyway, whose turn is it?

383
00:21:02,209 --> 00:21:03,089
Yours!

384
00:21:03,568 --> 00:21:06,127
-Yeah, it's yours.
-Mine? It's not my turn.

385
00:21:06,367 --> 00:21:07,886
-Yes, it is!
-I went like last month.

386
00:21:08,046 --> 00:21:09,006
-He went two weeks.
-You never went.

387
00:21:09,166 --> 00:21:11,085
-Last month.
-Are you nuts? I went right after him.

388
00:21:11,245 --> 00:21:11,884
I'm not going.

389
00:21:12,084 --> 00:21:13,004
-Why?
-It's too hot.

390
00:21:13,364 --> 00:21:15,003
If I walk down the
stairs, I'll pass out.

391
00:21:18,601 --> 00:21:20,240
Mustard and onions. No soda.

392
00:21:20,760 --> 00:21:21,799
I know you!

393
00:21:22,279 --> 00:21:23,558
I look like a lot of people.

394
00:21:24,558 --> 00:21:25,637
The scam was simple.

395
00:21:26,197 --> 00:21:29,076
I was to walk up to the hot dog
vendor and order what I wanted.

396
00:21:29,595 --> 00:21:32,754
The vendor would then hand me my hot
dog and watch as I ran off without paying.

397
00:21:33,314 --> 00:21:35,952
This left the vendor with two
choices, neither very appealing.

398
00:21:36,472 --> 00:21:39,430
He could stand his ground and swallow
his loss, or he could give chase.

399
00:21:40,070 --> 00:21:41,669
The second forces him
to abandon the cart...

400
00:21:41,829 --> 00:21:43,668
...where my friends could
feast in his absence.

401
00:21:46,827 --> 00:21:48,346
I'm gonna need two napkins?

402
00:21:50,225 --> 00:21:51,504
Pay my money, thief!

403
00:21:58,821 --> 00:21:59,740
Wow! Ketchup!

404
00:21:59,820 --> 00:22:01,100
I took it from him and ran!

405
00:22:01,499 --> 00:22:05,178
I scooted past Tommy Mug's Dry
Cleaners and Armond's Shoe Repair.

406
00:22:05,897 --> 00:22:09,655
The vendor gave chase, a wooden-
handled, pronged fork in one hand.

407
00:22:11,334 --> 00:22:12,134
You gonna give me two?

408
00:22:22,489 --> 00:22:24,088
You know, these things are
heavier than they look.

409
00:22:24,288 --> 00:22:27,127
Genius, it's the gas tanks
to keep the food hot.

410
00:22:27,326 --> 00:22:28,566
They're heavier than shit!

411
00:22:29,326 --> 00:22:30,805
Think we can push it, the three of us?

412
00:22:31,724 --> 00:22:32,764
Push it where?

413
00:22:33,324 --> 00:22:35,882
A couple of blocks. It'll be
a nice surprise for the guy...

414
00:22:36,202 --> 00:22:38,601
...when he comes back from chasing
Shakes, not to find his cart.

415
00:22:59,071 --> 00:23:00,870
The vendor tired at 47th and 9th.

416
00:23:01,310 --> 00:23:02,789
I was on the other side of the street.

417
00:23:04,788 --> 00:23:06,707
He was beat...but not beaten.

418
00:23:07,506 --> 00:23:09,665
He could go ten minutes
more, just on hate alone.

419
00:23:10,145 --> 00:23:13,264
Give it up.

420
00:23:26,057 --> 00:23:26,857
What's wrong, Mikey?

421
00:23:27,976 --> 00:23:30,815
Shakes is taking too long.
He should've been back by now.

422
00:23:31,654 --> 00:23:33,373
He'll be fine. He's Shakes.

423
00:23:36,292 --> 00:23:38,331
You guys were supposed to take
the hot dogs, not the wagon.

424
00:23:39,011 --> 00:23:40,770
-Now he tells us.
-He's coming fast, Mikey.

425
00:23:40,930 --> 00:23:41,849
He still near?

426
00:23:42,529 --> 00:23:44,288
I got a plan! Come on
over by the subway!

427
00:23:45,327 --> 00:23:48,686
The plan was as simple and as dumb
as anything we had ever done.

428
00:23:49,565 --> 00:23:51,644
We were to hold the cart on the top
edge of the stairwell,

429
00:23:51,724 --> 00:23:53,883
Leaning it downward,
and wait for the vendor.

430
00:23:54,083 --> 00:23:55,922
We were to let it go the second
he grabbed the handles.

431
00:23:56,082 --> 00:23:59,121
Then we'd leave the scene as he struggled
to ease the cart back onto the sidewalk.

432
00:23:59,680 --> 00:24:01,759
To this day, I don't
know why we did it.

433
00:24:02,199 --> 00:24:03,598
But, we would all pay a price.

434
00:24:04,358 --> 00:24:08,116
It only took a minute...but
in that minute...everything changed.

435
00:24:09,355 --> 00:24:10,275
Guys, I can't hold it!

436
00:24:10,435 --> 00:24:12,074
-Don't let go!
-I can't hold it!

437
00:24:14,313 --> 00:24:14,993
I can't hold it!

438
00:24:28,106 --> 00:24:29,985
Stop! God, no! !

439
00:24:51,814 --> 00:24:52,614
Damn!

440
00:24:57,891 --> 00:25:01,609
Sweet Jesus! What have you boys done?

441
00:25:01,929 --> 00:25:04,568
What in the name of God
have you boys done?

442
00:25:04,648 --> 00:25:05,927
I think we just killed a man.

443
00:25:11,244 --> 00:25:14,203
While James Caldwell was slowly
recovering at St. Clare's Hospital...

444
00:25:14,963 --> 00:25:18,601
...we were charged and remanded
into our parents' custody.

445
00:25:19,600 --> 00:25:20,480
I'm sorry, dad.

446
00:25:20,840 --> 00:25:22,119
'Sorry' ain't gonna do you much good.

447
00:25:23,758 --> 00:25:26,277
Take it easy!
This is no time to get crazy!

448
00:25:27,476 --> 00:25:29,715
You're going to jail and you don't
even know what the fuck that means!

449
00:25:29,875 --> 00:25:31,434
Ma! Come look, Ma!

450
00:25:31,634 --> 00:25:33,833
I don't know. Bastard!

451
00:25:33,993 --> 00:25:36,392
He's just a kid!
He shouldn't have to do time!

452
00:25:36,552 --> 00:25:40,870
Nobody in this family should have to do
time. I done enough time for everybody!

453
00:26:06,177 --> 00:26:07,536
I hear you're short an altar boy.

454
00:26:11,414 --> 00:26:12,374
You still remember what to do?

455
00:26:14,133 --> 00:26:16,692
Easy on the water,
heavy on the wine.

456
00:26:17,611 --> 00:26:19,770
And ring the bells whenever
I see someone start to nod off.

457
00:26:20,930 --> 00:26:22,609
Get ready...we got 5 minutes
till show time.

458
00:26:35,282 --> 00:26:36,522
I'm gonna miss this.

459
00:26:39,640 --> 00:26:40,880
I'm gonna miss all of this.

460
00:26:42,799 --> 00:26:46,117
I've been doing all I can, but so
far every door I touch is locked.

461
00:26:50,795 --> 00:26:54,033
I could run...we all could run.

462
00:26:57,032 --> 00:26:58,191
Disappear for a while.

463
00:26:59,470 --> 00:27:00,470
Nobody's gonna come looking.

464
00:27:02,229 --> 00:27:06,347
Nobody's gonna care about us...
about where we go.

465
00:27:11,744 --> 00:27:14,303
You run now, you're gonna
run till you die.

466
00:27:16,782 --> 00:27:19,820
Hiding's not gonna make it go away.
People aren't gonna forget.

467
00:27:22,179 --> 00:27:23,298
You've gotta face this.

468
00:27:29,455 --> 00:27:30,495
I can't, Father.

469
00:27:33,054 --> 00:27:34,413
I don't want to face it.

470
00:27:36,572 --> 00:27:38,131
I'm too scared to face it.

471
00:27:40,090 --> 00:27:41,130
I'm scared, too.

472
00:27:42,049 --> 00:27:45,887
Nobody's more scared than I am,
but you gotta do it.

473
00:27:49,205 --> 00:27:52,564
You're gonna be okay. You're
gonna make it through there.

474
00:27:54,083 --> 00:27:54,883
You understand?

475
00:28:00,440 --> 00:28:01,919
Come on. We got an audience.

476
00:28:09,435 --> 00:28:11,954
I counted three rummies and
four widows on my way in.

477
00:28:14,673 --> 00:28:17,112
Plus Fat Ralphie sleeping
one off in the last row.

478
00:28:18,951 --> 00:28:21,269
It's the rain. Bad weather
always brings in the crowds.

479
00:28:27,266 --> 00:28:28,546
This is one of my favorites.

480
00:28:29,825 --> 00:28:30,785
What is?

481
00:28:32,504 --> 00:28:36,302
"Whatever you do to the least of
my brethren...you do to me."

